          text: "[COMPANY_NAME] defines granular handling requirements for each classification level across the entire information lifecycle. These requirements establish the minimum acceptable controls for each classification tier. Information Owners retain the authority to impose additional or more stringent requirements based on specific regulatory mandates, contractual obligations, legal considerations, or risk assessments applicable to their data. When multiple classification levels apply to a single system, dataset, or document, the handling requirements of the highest applicable level shall govern.\n\nLow Impact handling requirements are as follows. Storage is permitted on standard [COMPANY_NAME] information systems, organization-managed endpoints, and approved cloud services operating under the organization's standard service agreements. Access control requires standard user authentication to organizational systems; role-based access controls at the system or application level are sufficient, and no per-dataset access authorization by the Information Owner is required. Transmission may occur via standard organizational email, approved collaboration and messaging platforms, and standard file transfer methods within and between organizational systems. Encryption of Low Impact data in transit is encouraged but not mandatory when transmitted within the organizational network; encryption is required when transmitting over public networks. Labeling is optional for individual documents but recommended for collections and repositories. Printing and reproduction are permitted without specific restrictions beyond standard business need. Physical copies may be stored in standard office environments. Disposal of electronic data follows standard deletion procedures; formal data sanitization is not required. Paper documents may be disposed of through standard recycling.\n\nModerate Impact handling requirements are as follows. Storage is restricted to access-controlled [COMPANY_NAME] information systems, organization-managed endpoints, and approved cloud services whose security posture has been assessed and confirmed to meet [COMPANY_NAME] requirements for Moderate Impact data. Personally managed devices, personal cloud storage, and unauthorized third-party services are prohibited. Access control requires role-based access with documented authorization based on business need; access provisioning and de-provisioning shall be managed through a formal access request process. Information Owners shall review access lists at least annually. Transmission outside the [COMPANY_NAME] internal network or to external recipients must be encrypted using TLS 1.2 or higher for data in transit, or equivalent approved encryption. Email containing Moderate Impact data sent to external recipients should use encryption or be transmitted through a secure file sharing service. Labeling is required; all documents, files, emails, and data stores containing Moderate Impact information shall be marked with \"Internal Use Only\" or an equivalent classification label as approved by the information security team. Printing and reproduction shall be limited to authorized personnel using organization-controlled devices. Printed materials shall be secured when not in active use (clean desk policy). Printing to shared or public printers is prohibited unless the individual retrieves the output immediately. Disposal of electronic media shall use secure deletion tools that perform at minimum a single-pass overwrite, or shall rely on encryption with documented key destruction. Removable media shall be sanitized using NIST SP 800-88 Clear procedures. Paper documents shall be cross-cut shredded using a shredder that produces particles no larger than 2mm x 15mm (P-4 or higher per DIN 66399).\n\nHigh Impact handling requirements are as follows. Storage must employ encryption at rest using FIPS 140-2 validated cryptographic modules or equivalent approved encryption, with encryption keys managed in accordance with the key management procedures of [COMPANY_NAME]. High Impact data shall be stored only on systems with enhanced access controls including individually assigned permissions, comprehensive audit logging capturing all access and modification events, and integrity monitoring. Storage on removable media is prohibited except with explicit written approval from the Information Owner and the Chief Information Security Officer. Access control requires explicit, individually authorized access approved by the Information Owner for each individual or narrowly defined role. Multi-factor authentication is mandatory for all access to High Impact data. Privileged access to systems housing High Impact data shall be subject to enhanced monitoring and periodic review. Separation of duties shall be implemented where feasible to prevent any single individual from having unrestricted access to High Impact data and the systems that process it. Transmission must be encrypted end-to-end using approved encryption methods with key lengths and algorithms meeting current [COMPANY_NAME] cryptographic standards. Transmission shall occur only through designated secure channels pre-approved by the information security team. Email transmission of High Impact data is prohibited unless an approved email encryption solution is used. Wireless transmission of unencrypted High Impact data is prohibited under all circumstances. Labeling is mandatory; all documents, files, emails, presentations, and any other media containing High Impact data shall bear a clear \"Confidential\" marking or equivalent approved designation. Database fields and system records containing High Impact data shall be identified in the data classification inventory. Printing and reproduction shall be minimized to the greatest extent practicable. When printing is necessary, it shall be performed only on secure, dedicated printers located in physically controlled areas. All printed copies shall be numbered and tracked using a distribution log. Reproduction (copying, scanning, photographing) requires authorization from the Information Owner. Disposal of electronic media shall comply with NIST SP 800-88 Purge procedures, or the media shall be physically destroyed (degaussing, shredding, or incineration) by an approved destruction service. Certificates of destruction shall be obtained and retained. Paper documents shall be cross-cut shredded to a particle size no larger than 0.8mm x 12mm (P-5 or higher per DIN 66399), or incinerated. Bulk destructions of High Impact paper documents shall be witnessed by a minimum of two authorized personnel, with a destruction certificate signed by both witnesses."
